You could use `UNION ALL`, like:

    select case 
    	when exists (select 1 from all where primary ilike &#39;%phy%&#39;)
    		then &#39;Failed&#39;
    		else &#39;Passed&#39;
    	end result
    union all 
    select case 
    	when exists (select 1 from all where primary ilike &#39;%org%&#39;)
    		then &#39;Failed&#39;
    		else &#39;Passed&#39;
    	end

Note: noth `primary` and `all` are reserved words in Postgres: don&#39;t use them in real life.

You would normally use an `IF EXISTS()`
as:

```
IF EXISTS(select * from all
where primary like &#39;%phy%&#39;
limit 1;)
THEN
SELECT &#39;Failed&#39;
ELSE SELECT &#39;Passed&#39;
end if

union all

IF EXISTS(select * from all
where primary like &#39;%org%&#39;
limit 1;)
THEN
SELECT &#39;Failed&#39;
ELSE SELECT &#39;Passed&#39;
end if
```

