Your code is written all wrong.

The statement `char symb[5];` declares a fixed sized array that can hold 5 `char` elements max.  But when you do `cin &gt;&gt; symb[5];`, you are not reading *up to* 5 `char`s into the array, you are reading *a single* `char` into the **6th** slot of the array, corrupting surrounding memory.

Also, `symb[5] == &#39;co2&#39;` is not the right way to compare the contents of the array.  You are comparing the **6th** (invalid) `char` against a single multi-byte character, you are not comparing the whole content of the array against a multi-character string.

Try something more like this instead:

```c++
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;cstring&gt;
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    char symb[5];

    cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Enter Symbol: &quot;;
    cin.get(symb, 5);

    if (strcmp(symb, &quot;co2&quot;) == 0)
    {
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;This is Carbon-Dioxide&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
    else
    {
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Error&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

That being said, using a `std::string` instead of a `char[]` is better:

```c++
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    string symb;

    cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Enter Symbol: &quot;;
    cin &gt;&gt; symb;

    if (symb == &quot;co2&quot;)
    {
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;This is Carbon-Dioxide&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
    else
    {
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Error&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

